, analysing the intriguing afterlives of characters such as Jane Eyre and Rochester in neo-Victorian fiction, cinema, television, the stage and, more recently, on the web. Taking a fresh look at 150 years of engagement with one of the best-loved novelists of the Victorian period, from obituaries to vlogs, from stage to screen, from novels to erotic makeovers, this book reveals the author’s diverse and intriguing legacy. Engagingly written and illustrated, the book will appeal to both scholars and general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBronte biodrama.  aElizabeth Gaskell.  aMary Taylor.  aVictorian period.  aVirginia Woolf.  acultural afterlife.  alabour migration.  aliterary pilgrimage.  aliterary tourism.  alyric afterlife.  amiddle-class women.  amigration.  amobility.  apopular culture.1 aBarton, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraxton, Kimberley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiggins, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathieson, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiesse, Jude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPietrzak- Franger, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoore, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPouliot, Amber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r